The paper deals with the problem of power allocation in a wireless charging network, which involves multiple users with different demand urgencies. This problem can be viewed as a game-theoretic problem, where each user aims to maximize its own utility function. Therefore, the paper is likely to belong to the Game Theory (cs.GT) sub-category. 

Moreover, the paper also involves the design of a distributed algorithm for power allocation, which requires the coordination of multiple agents in the network. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. 

In addition, the paper deals with the convergence analysis of the distributed algorithm under different scenarios, such as synchronous and asynchronous scheduling, communication delay, and packet drops. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Systems and Control (cs.SY) sub-category, as well as the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. 

Finally, the paper involves numerical simulations to validate the correctness of the analysis and demonstrate the performance of the algorithm. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Machine Learning (cs.MA) sub-category, as machine learning techniques are often used for simulation and data analysis.
